‚úÖ Ubuntu Training Handbook ‚Äì Part 1 (Modules 1‚Äì10)

üî∞ Module 1: Introduction to Ubuntu
whoami       # Show current user
hostname     # Show system hostname
uname -a     # Show OS and kernel info


üß∞ Module 2: Basic File Commands
mkdir test_folder     # Create new folder
cd test_folder        # Navigate into folder
touch file1.txt       # Create an empty file
ls -l                 # List files with details
la		# list all files (incl hidden files)
rm file1.txt          # Delete a file
cd ..                 # Go up one level
rmdir test_folder     # Remove empty folder


Command
Description
Example
ls -lh filename
Shows file size in human-readable format (KB, MB)
ls -lh myfile.txt
du -h filename
Shows disk usage of a file (human-readable)
du -h cron_test.log
du -sh filename
Shows only the total size (suppress file name listing)
du -sh myfile.txt
stat filename
Detailed file info including size in bytes
stat myfile.txt
stat -c%s filename
Outputs only the file size in bytes
stat -c%s myfile.txt
du -sh *
Shows sizes of all files and folders in the current directory
du -sh *
du -sh /path/to/folder
Shows total size of a specific folder
du -sh ~/Downloads
find . -type f -exec du -h {} +
Lists all file sizes recursively
find . -type f -exec du -h {} +
ls -lhS
Lists files in the current directory sorted by size (descending)
ls -lhS
`du -a
sort -n -r
head -n 10`



üìÇ Module 3: File Viewing and Editing
echo "Ubuntu Training" > sample.txt   # Create file with text
cat sample.txt                       # View file content
nano sample.txt                      # Edit file using nano


üì¶ Module 4: Package Management
sudo apt update                      # Update package list
sudo apt upgrade                     # Upgrade installed packages
sudo apt install cowsay              # Install cowsay app
cowsay "Hello, Ubuntu!"              # Run cowsay (or) flag -f ‚Üí cowsay -f moose ‚Äúhi‚Äù
sudo apt remove cowsay               # Uninstall cowsay


üë• Module 5: User Management
sudo adduser testuser               # Create a new users
su - testuser		#substitute user
quit
sudo usermod -aG sudo testuser      # Add user to sudo group
sudo deluser testuser               # Delete user


üîê Module 6: File Permissions
touch file.txt                      # Create a file
ls -l file.txt                      # Show permissions
Ls -lh file.txt		#human readable in bytes
chmod 755 file.txt                  # Change permissions
ls -l file.txt                      # Confirm change

Ex: 	-rw-rw-r-- 1 testuser testuser 0 Jul 14 19:57 file.txt
rw- ‚Üí Owner: can read and write
	r-- ‚Üí Group: can read
	r-- ‚Üí Others: can read

Octal
Symbolic
Meaning
7
rwx
Read, write, execute
6
rw-
Read, write
5
r-x
Read, execute
4
r--
Read only
0
---
No permissions

Example:
 chmod 755 file ‚Üí rwxr-xr-x (or) 600 is 100% private

üåê Module 7: Networking Basics
ip a                                # Show IP address info
ping -c 4 google.com                # Test internet connection


üß™ Module 8: Bash Scripting Intro
Create the script:
nano hello.sh

Paste into file:
#!/bin/bash
echo "Welcome to Ubuntu!"

Then run:
chmod +x hello.sh                  # Make script executable
./hello.sh                         # Execute script


üóÇÔ∏è Module 9: System Monitoring
top                                 # Live system monitor
htop                                # Advanced process viewer
free -h                             # Check memory usage
df -h                               # Disk space usage

Ex:
# Create script
echo -e '#!/bin/bash\nwhile true; do echo "Looping..."; sleep 2; done' > loop.sh
chmod +x loop.sh

# Run in background
./loop.sh &

# Find PID
pgrep -f loop.sh

# Kill process by PID
kill PID

(If htop is not installed: sudo apt install htop)

üîç Module 10: Searching and Finding Files
sudo updatedb                      # Update locate database
locate bash                        # Find files containing 'bash'
find /etc -name "*.conf"           # Find all .conf files in /etc
grep 'root' /etc/passwd            # Search for 'root' in passwd

If not available ‚Äúsudo apt install plocate‚Äù


